segments.text: Yeah, go ahead.
You were telling us about his recruiting.
Yeah, about Charlie Moran.
Well, we used to play two games a week with Texas at that time because they were the big money, big gates.
And Charlie beat Texas University so regular that it hurt them.
They couldn't stand it.
And it wound up into a big street fight down there in Houston after the game.
And we run all the Texas University guys off the Houston streets because we were all in uniform.
We knew what we were doing.
In fact, I think in all that disturbance, we came back to College Station with about five revolvers that we took off of the police that tried to stop us.
and their badges and their blackjacks.
So after about three years of that, both schools were suffering because they missed that gate.
And they got together.
The athletic council from both schools got together.
talked it over and Texas said they wouldn't play us unless we got rid of Charlie Moran and that was the upshot of that.
We gave Charlie a farewell dress parade in the winter there when it was pouring down pouring down rain and I'm telling you it's one of the

One of the things I'll always remember, we rode him, we rode, we put Charlie on a wagon, and he and Mrs. Moran and Tommy, he was a little boy there, a boy about that, like that, rode him down to the railroad station.
They were leaving there on that four, that three or four o'clock train that came through there at that time going north, H&TC.
Well, they, uh,
We played, first game we played was in 1915, and we played at College Station.
That was one of the agreements they made, that they would play alternately at A&M and at Texas University.
So that first game, just before the game, this new coach that we had said, boys, I want to read you a telegram.
And he says,
He says, go out there and kick the hell out of them for old Charlie.
Charlie.
Yeah, they sure did.
Go on with the branding incident.
Well, that led up to the branding incident.
So when they got talking about, you want to brand him, that steer with that 20 to 3 brand, we were sitting up there in a board session like you do, still do, I'm sure.
And we got talking back around about, let's go over there and brand that steer.
And it was right between semesters, end of January, somewhere along there, wasn't that, that mid-term semester end.
And we got talking about what we'd do, and he said, let's go over there and burn him.
They said, nobody seems to know what to do about it.
I said, well, I know what to do about it.
And I spent enough time.
I said, I know what we'll need.
He says, all we need is a good string of rope, a couple of running irons, and I said, get a
a plumber's pot, one of those heating pots, I think we can heat them irons on a plumber's pot.
And that one of the guys was in there, his father was a contractor in Waco by the name of O.K.
Johnson.
And O.K.
says, I know where to get that.
He says, we got all that kind of equipment.
And he says, I'll furnish the car.
Well, when a man says he furnished a car at that time, back in 1915, that was something.

So we all decided, we said, well, let's ask for a little leave of absence for a couple of days, and we'll go on up to Waco and get our equipment and slip down to Austin that evening, and we'll put the brand on.
We went down there, and Abe Bull, you may have met Abe, I don't know him.
Abe got to be a pretty big boy.
He'd come out of Austin and married into a banker's family and succeeded the family in the office, became chairman of the board there at the time of his death.
But Abe was just a sort of a teller or something in there about that time.
Or maybe he wasn't even married, he was just still.
And Abe said, now don't mention my name
as having anything to do about this brand he said, because I'm living over there.
So we never did mention the name in there about having anything to do with that brand.
But we slept in there.
Oh, we got in there about 7 o'clock at night.
And he knew where they kept him down there and they had a barn.
down there where they kept him.
Of course, there was nothing to it but putting a brand on him.
Just went down there and threw a loop on him, snared him up to a post and went down and looped him around his iron legs and pulled him down and tied him up.
Got a heating pot, good and hot, put irons in there and put a red big 13 to nothing brand on him.
Branded him from
from his shoulder, went back to his hip.
There was a young fellow down there on the campus, a photographer.
He went to school there.
But he was a pretty fair photographer.
And he went over there and took a picture of him.
And when we got back to Waco, that's when we got our first publicity on that deal.
We got in there, and there was old Jim Grove.
Of course, Jim and his family is an old family in Waco, too.
They operated a laundry there for years and years.
And we were down there on the street,
And there's a young fella came up there, and he knew Jim, and got talking and talking, and Jim was telling him what we had done, that we'd just been down to Austin and branded that Longhorn still.
And he, oh, he was very much interested.
He said, I want to get the story for the paper.
Got all that in there, and then he took us out to Cameron Park
and snapped a bunch of pictures, and wrote up the story, and it came out, and all the other papers got a rerun on it.
It'd run in all the papers, and it'd run.
San Antonio paper, Houston paper, Dallas paper.
Nobody ever saw you while you were over there doing it?
No.
Oh, no way.
Did you do it at night?
Yeah, at night.
About what time?
It was about midnight.
About midnight.
About midnight.
It was close to midnight.
I know it was, oh, man, it was a...
It was one of them clear, briskly cold nights.
You know, everything just twinkled, frosty as it could be.
Well, was there much excitement after everybody found out what you'd done?
Oh, uh...
It rankled Austin, the student body over there, terrifically.
I know they, we went over there just a short while over after that to play basketball.
And rolled over there on the whole cadet corps went over there.
It almost wound up into a, into a, into a big,
fight right there on the basketball field inside the gym where they played the game.
Oh, gee, they were mad.
There were a couple of basketball, a couple of football players.
I remember that one, Texas University.
Was his name McCollum?
McCollum or some such name.
He just jumped up and down.
We were sitting right here.
I had a seat right on the floor of the gym, and right across the court on the other side was a bunch of football players over there.
They were just hollering at one another the whole time.
And what year now did you graduate?
What did you do after you graduated?
Wasn't there, Army?
Practically the entire senior class went into service.
There were a few for special reasons that couldn't leave right then, but I think at least 95% of them went right into service.
From then, when I got out of the service, I came down here and went to farming.
Where were you stationed then when you were in the service?
What did you do?
I was in the 64th Infantry, regular army.
And where were you most of that time?
Well, on this side, I was stationed for a while at Fort Bliss.
And I was also, later when we were brigaded, just before we moved across, we were brigaded at Waco.
forget what they called that army post there.
And from there we moved right on up to Hoboken where we caught the boat.
Where did you land?
At Brest.
It's an old army barracks of Brest.
They said it was a barracks

about that uh where um caesar at the time of his invasion of england where he took off when he went across the channel did you see any combat while you were there yes we were in combat for uh just we came in on the tail end of it and we got over there in september and went right into the line then we stayed there until it was a holding deal
It was a holding deal there.
It had quieted down.
Real active fighting had kind of moved around because they were almost stalemated.
They were run right up against a heavy fortified area right around Brest.
Brest was an old German army setup.
It was heavily, very heavily fortified.
and it had brought the, it had brought the, you might say the, our advance to a standstill, and they were moving around toward the left.
And they left us there to hold until, until they could weaken fresh, I'd say, action.
And then we could move in.
We were due to move in
We were due to move in on the 11th of November.
And I know on the 11th, when we were still on the line there, on the holding position, just artillery and a little skirmish upon the line.
That's all that amounted to.
I remember how quiet that artillery sound got it on the limo.
It just kept getting more quiet, more quiet until it stopped.
And I mean when it stopped it looked like it just made more noise than ever.
After you've been sitting in artillery area or offense for
about 60 days, it really gets quiet when it stops or it gets loud.
And you came then to the valley here after World War I.
And you went to farming?
Yeah.
What did you farm?
What were your major crops?
Oh, I grew some general field crops and vegetables.
At that time, the, uh, the, uh, Cetrus deal had not developed.
It was a little before the Cetrus deal developed.
And then I, uh, I, uh, like I say, after I formed a while, I never had formed in my life until I came down here.
But after I found out,
got on to how it was supposed to be done, I got to making some money out of it.
And, like I said, after I made some money, I got into the stock market.
Then I traded my deal down here for some property in Dallas and hit that just in the time of the Depression and lost it up there.
Came back with my pocket junkie.
What'd you do then?
Then what'd you do?
Your flat broke then, so you couldn't start over?
What I did after that?
Yeah.
That's what I said.
I saw the footloose.
I wasn't able to establish any claim to a job with the Extension Department.
And that friend of mine says, if you want to go in the beer business, I'll set you up.
And I went into the beer bin this far.
What year was this that you went into the beer bin?
That was in about 34.
So it's after it became legal again.
Yeah.
And so what'd you do?
You opened up a tavern.
Mm-hmm.
How long did you keep your tavern?
Until about 40, 45.
I sold out in about 45.
And then what'd you do?
Well, I dabbled around real estate for a couple years.
and made some money.
And then I went into the stock market here.
By that time, I had me a pretty fair little bankroll, and I went into the, and I acquired me a pretty nice block of stocks on the stock market.
Until a friend of mine came along, who was broke, and he was going to make me some money out of it.
on an adventure that he had.
And I didn't want to do it, but he finally got me down.
I sold my stock and went into him and then lost that.
I salvaged enough out of that deal to get another foothold and wound up with what I got.
I see.
And then you're retired now.
Yeah, I haven't done anything for about 12, oh, about 15 years.
I see.
My health got pretty bad.
That one stage, I don't know just what it was.
I went to see quite a bunch of doctors, clinics.
My neighbor came over here to see me.
I was sitting around him.
sitting there talking, but they came in here to visit with me.
I see them now every once in a while, and they laugh at me.
They said, yeah, ask me if I remember the time they came in here and talked to me, because they didn't think I was going to live till morning.
Thank you, Mr. Rothy.
You've given me a great deal of useful information.
I certainly appreciate it.
Well...
